# Chapter 1Introduction

Welcome to an Introduction to Computer Programming. With these series of lessons, we aim to introduce the power of computer programming using fun and unique methods. In many ways, computer programming is quickly becoming a skill as necessary as using email. And it is believed that becoming fluent in a programming language is far more useful than being fluent in any foreign.  We have programs that can translate a foreign language anyways! ;)

Almost every profession uses software to manage their business, and computer programmes are increasingly needed to develop **this** software. Which is a reason why individuals skilled in Software Development are in high demand. And software is the ultimate tool for aspiring entrepreneurs. Armed with nothing more than a computer and internet, and developers can make profits with simple ideas.

What to Expect

These series of classes will attempt to introduce you and your student to the world of computer programming on a technical level.  And I must emphasize _technical level_.  The buzz word STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math) is a hot topic right now.  Hundreds of millions of dollars are being spent on programs and initiatives to introduce STEM to kids K-12, in an effort to prepare students for the jobs of the future.  What's important to recognize is the subtle difference between "exposing" our students to STEM-related careers and "preparing" them for these careers.

STEM careers require a unique ability to create things that don't already exists, with no exact instruction on how to create it.  Exposing students to computer programming relates to what I like to call the TRAIN CONDUCTOR EXPERIENCE:

**"Type 'Right' twice to see the ball bounce across the screen"**.

But PREPARING students for computer programming actually relates to:

**"Create a program that will allow fellow students to bounce a ball by typing 'Right' twice".**

We will aim to prepare students to use their skills and become creators of technology. And we will strive to introduce these concepts in a format that identifies specifically with parents and students of color.



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Who Should Read This

You should! These workbooks are written to be understood by middle and high school students, but also fun for adults as well. Parents and teachers are encouraged to use these activities to introduce your students to computer programming.

Remember that the fields of STEM require constant learning.  And the ""#1 skill that is needed for any student is the ability to be a Self-Learner"".  Above anything else, you should train yourself to be a problem solver.  Given your computer and access to the internet, challenge yourself to find out how to do the things that you can't do.  And when the answer isn't clear, TRY your own solution until you get it right.  This is the joy of STEM!



Getting Started



Before we get too deep into our coding, lets take a step back to talk about computers in general.  Computers are represented by many different things, besides just the normal laptop or desktop.  Cell phones are computers, smartTVs are computers, video game systems, and more.  And to keep it simple, all computers are made of two things: Hardware and Software.

Hardware

The hardware of a computer is anything that you can feel and touch.  The physical parts of a computer.  The metal and pieces that make up the devices that we use.  These pieces include keyboards, mouse, monitor, Playstation, cell, wires, and more.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Software

If hardware is the parts and pieces of a computer, then Software is the brains of the computer.  It tells the hardware on the computer exactly what to do and how to do it.  You can't touch or feel software, but without it, the computer would just be a pile of metals and screws.  The software tells the computer what to show on the screen, what happens when you send a text, and how many points you'll score when playing the Michael Jackson Experience on Wii.  Software can be the video games that we play, the apps on our phones, the desktop applications like Microsoft Word, and even social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Computer Languages

The focus of our work will be with software, and how to write code that will create software of all types.  Let's think of software as a set of instructions for the computer to follow.  We write code to give the computer instructions, and the computer follows our instructions exactly as told.  (NOTE: Computers are dumb like this, and will always do EXACTLY as they are told.  Nothing more nothing less.)

This process is no different than us giving instructions to another person:

**"Go to the kitchen and bring back a glass of water"**

That is a clear instruction for a human being.  And, if they are a nice friend, they will understand and go bring back the water as instructed.  But if we chose to, we could also give those exact same instructions in many different languages besides English.  We could have said this in Yuroba, Spanish, Swahili, French, Arabic, and more.

**"Go bring me a glass of water"** - English

**"L mu mi a gilasi ti omi."** - Yuroba

**"Ir traerme un vaso de agua."** - Spanish

**"Aller apportez-moi un verre d'eau."** - French

All of these instructions are saying the same thing, but using different languages.  Computer programming languages are the same way.  We use programming languages to tell computers to follow all kinds of instructions like showing web pages, responding to buttons pressed on the keyboard, or uploading photos from our phones.  And we can use any one of many different computer programming languages to get this accomplished.  Some of these languages include:

Java

PHP

C++

C#

Perl

Ruby

.NET

Python

Javascript

HTML

and more

For example, to print the words "Hello World" to the computer screen you could use instructions like these from several languages:

**System.out.println("Hello World");** - Java

**print("Hello World")** - PHP

**console.log('Hello World');** - Javascript

**<div>Hello World</div>** - HTML

As a future computer software developer, you will find yourself becoming familiar with one or many of these languages.  And you will also spend time translating between different types of languages.  In this book, we will be primarily using the Javascript and HTML programming languages.



First Program

To learn computer programming we are going to PROGRAM.  Simple enough right?  And to do this we are going to start with the programming language Javascript.  Let's get started!

Once installed, open Google Chrome and type **about:blank** in the address bar.  This should open a blank page in the browser.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

As mentioned, we will be using the Google Chrome Javascript Developer Console to write and test our code.  To start using this console from the browser, hold down the **CTRL** and **SHIFT** keys and press the **J** key.  (If you are using a Mac computer, hold down the **COMMAND** and **OPTION** keys while pressing **J** ).

You should still see your blank page, but now you should also see a console with a right angle bracket (>) and a blinking cursor ( | ).  This is where we will be writing and running our code.  Let's try this out to make sure everything is working.  Type the following by your cursor and then press the **ENTER** key:

**1+1;**

Pressing **ENTER** tells our console to run the program that we just typed.  If everything is working correctly, you should see the answer (2) as output.

CONGRATS!  You just wrote your first Javascript program.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Challenge Yourself:

Instead of 1+1, use the Javascript Development Console to calculate how many points were scored by a college basketball team.  In basketball, a Basket is worth 2 points, a 3-Point Shot is worth 3 points, and a Free Throw is worth 1 point.

Assuming your team made twenty Baskets, five 3-Point Shots, and fifteen Free Throws, use one line of Javascript code how many total points did your team score?  (Hint: Similar to your classroom math, you can use parentheses in Javascript.)

Working with Variables

As future software developers, we will use plenty of data while writing our various programs.  Data such as the number of Facebook friends to show on the screen, the number of points generated on the Candy Crush, or even the number of touchdowns scored on NFL Madden 2016.  Any good program will require us to keep track and manage data, because this is the information that will make our program work correctly.

So if data is the information that we need in our programs, Variables are the way that we reference and manage that data.  ( **"What in the world does that mean??"** ).  Variables are used to store data in our program's memory to be used later.  Let's take a look at this using an example:

**var bank = 100;**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

With this statement, we are telling the computer to create a space in memory and place the value of 100 in it.

The word **var** is a keyword in Javascript that tells our program to create this memory location.  We get a chance to name this memory space whatever we like, so the word **bank** is the Variable name of the memory location.

Try typing **var bank = 100;** into your developer console and press **Enter**.  This should create your variable bank, assign the value of 100 to it, and return **undefined** to the screen.

Now type **bank;** and press **Enter**.  This will tell your program to return the value of the variable bank.  And this value is 100.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

NOTE: Wondering what the "undefined" meant?  Many times when we write statements we are requesting the program to return a value.  So the statement **bank;** asked our program to return the value of the variable called bank.  But the statement **var bank = 100;** was only used to create our variable, and did not return a value.  And our Google Chrome Development Console will always return "undefined" if no value is being returned.



Naming Variables

So we've discussed how to create variables and assign a value to them.  In our previous example we used the statement **var bank = 100;** to create a new variable called bank.  As a developer we can name our variables whatever we like, and we normally start them with a lowercase letter.

For instance, we could name our variable **money** by writing **var money = 100;**  This would have created a space in memory called money and set the value of 100 in it.  All of these can work to create a variable:

**var bank = 100;**

**var money = 100;**

**var cash = 100;**

**var bread = 100;**

**var klsdfj = 100;**

These statements all create variables, even the last one which is named klsdfj.  Obviously this isn't even a real word, but the program doesn't care.  If that's what we want to name it that's what it will name it.  However, as developers we like to give variables names that make sense and reminds us about the value that we are looking to store.

Occasionally, we may want to use more than one word to name our variables.  For instance, your program may need to store the value of money in your bank account AND your friend's bank account.

**var account = 100;**

**var account = 300;**

If you needed to grab the value of just your account later in your program, how would you know which value to use?  Because of that very reason, programming languages typically will not allow you to create two variables with the same name.  So this is a great opportunity to use a name with a little more description.

**var myAccount = 100;**

**var friendAccount = 100;**

In programming languages, variable names can only be ONE word.  To get around this, developers will place two words together to create one word.  (Remember it doesn't matter to the computer what our name is.).  In order to read it better, we will capitalize the first letter of the second word as seen above.

Speaking of capitalization, it absolutely important in most coding languages.  This means that case matters.  Let's take a look at the following example:

**var myAccount = 100;**

**var myaccount = 400;**

Be careful with case when programming!  To most programming languages, these represent two different variables simply because the "A" in the name is lowercase for one and uppercase for the other.  So make sure you are consistent with your choice of words!

Challenge Yourself:

The Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was landmark legislation in the United States that outlawed discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex and national origin.

Create two variables in your Javascript Development Console.  One variable should have the value of the year of the Civil Rights Act.  The other should have the value of the year that you was born.

Hint: After creating the variable, you can type the name of your variable and press **ENTER** to see the value displayed on the screen.



Manipulating Variable Values

Variables are used to store values in memory that can be used later.  We can also change the value in those variables.

Declare a variable called 'bank', and set it's value to 100.  Then set it's value to 200.

**var bank = 100;**

**bank = 200;**

WHY DIDN'T YOU HAVE TO USE THE KEYWORD 'var' WHEN CHANGING THE VALUE TO 200?

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

We can also use the value in one variable and assign it to another variable:

**var bank = 100;**

**var newBalance = 400;**

**bank = newBalance;**

After these lines are executed, the value in variable 'bank' is 400;  The value of 'newBalance' remains 400;

# WEBSITES EXPLAINED:

Web programming refers to the markup and coding of website development.  This includes the website content, the use of data and databases, security, and communicating with other web programs called web services.

Browsers

Browsers have become the primary way we access the internet and the information of the world.  Almost all computers are sold with at least the Internet Explorer or Safari software applications already installed.  And if you're like me, you're a big fan of the Firefox and Google Chrome browsers as well.  All of these applications take a URL (ex. " [http://www.scratchwerk.net](http://www.scratchwerk.net)") and displays the website for that URL.

WHAT BROWSER APPLICATIONS DO YOU USE?

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

_HTML Translation_

Websites look pretty in our browsers, but they are actually created and formatted using a markup language called HTML.  The term HTML stands for Hypertext Markup Language, and is a standard way for us to manage font, color, images, links and more on our websites.  The job of the browser is to translate this HTML format into a visual representation on our screen.

To understand this concept, let's view some page source to see how this works.  Open up Firefox or Google Chrome and visit any website, (ex " [http://www.scratchwerk.net](http://www.scratchwerk.net)). What you see is the visual translation of HTML code.  The see the actual HTML source code that written, **hold down Crtl and press U**.  This will open a window displaying the HTML code that the browser translated.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Looks confusing huh?  Don't worry, we will make this code make sense to you later.  But translating this into something pretty is the job of the browser.  But how does the browser find this HTML code when you type in the website name???

_File Types_

If you've ever spent time on a computer, you've interacted with different file types.  If writing a paper in Microsoft Word, you save create and save your file as a Word file type.  Word files are typically created with a **.doc** or **.docx** at the end (ex. "myessay.doc" or "christmaslist.docx").

Other file types include:

Excel files - usually end in .xls

Music files - usually end in .mp3

Image files - usually end in .png, .jpg, or .gif

PDF files - usually end in .pdf

and many more

Establishing a filetype for our files lets a programs and applications know how to use the file.  So our Word program knows how to read and use a file ending in .doc.  Our music players know how to use files ending in .mp3.  And so on.

Browsers specifically know how to read and use HTML filetypes ending in .html.  As we saw earlier, these HTML files will contain the source HTML code that our browser uses to translate into a visual.  These files are created and placed in file folders on the computer just like a Word files.

LETS TRY THIS OUT:

Create a new file in Notepad++ or TextWrangler and type in EXACTLY the following:

**<html>**

**<body>**

**<div>Hello World!</div>**

**</body>**

**</html>**

Save this as a HTML file with the name **"hello.hml"**.  (Be sure to select the filetype as HTML, and take note of the folder that you are saving it in.  I saved mine in a folder called C:/Scratchwerk/Website . )

To view the web page we just created, open up Firefox or Chrome and type in the URL below.  Replacing C:/Scratchwerk/Website with the file folder that you used:

**file:///C:/Scratchwerk/Website/hello.html**

This should open up a page saying "Hello World!".  Like the previous website we visited, lets **hold down Crtl and press U** to view the source HTML code that we wrote.



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Domains and Web Servers

So we've just created an amazing website that says "Hello World!".  But how is the world actually going to see it??  If the person next to you typed " **file:///C:/Scratchwerk/Website/hello.html**" into their browser it won't show anything because that HTML file is only on your computer.

This problem is solved using what is called Web Servers.  Servers are computers, (just like the one you are using now), that stay on and connected to the internet 24 hours a day / 7 days a week.  They are typically dedicated computers, which means no one is using them for personal use.  But we create files and save files on these computers just like on our personal computer.  Web Servers are normally used to hold ----you guessed it---- HTML and other website files like hello.html .

Web hosting companies such as GoDaddy have several Web Server computers connected to the internet that remain ON all the time.  They then change customers a small fee to save ("host") their HTML files on those servers instead of their local personal computer.

Why is this important?  Because these server computers are always ON and connected to the internet, anyone can access the HTML files that you created.  To do so, we can create and use Domain Names (ex. "espn.com", "facebook.com", "scratchwerk.net").  Domain Names are a registered URL that we can use to direct people to the web servers where our files are located.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once again for a small fee, Individuals or organizations can register and own a Domain Name.  As an example, I own the Domain Name **"scratchwerk.net"**.  As the owner of this domain, I can decide which web server to direct users to when they type the URL [http://www.scratchwerk.net](http://www.scratchwerk.net) into their browser.  Of course the web server that I use contains all the HTML files for my website.  Hosting companies like GoDaddy also sell domain names, but it's possible to own a Domain Name with one company, and host your files on a server provided by another.

HTML Basics

As we mentioned previously,  HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) is a standard way for us to manage font, color, images, links and more on our websites.  Browsers help us navigate the internet by translating HTML files into websites that are easier to look at.

Tags

Markup languages such as HTML consist of a set of tags, and each of these tags describes a different type of content.  These tags are created using the name of the tag with angle brackets surrounding it.

**<**** tagname ****>content**** < ****/tagname**** >**

Normally HTML tags come in pairs, with a start and end tag.  The end tag looks just like the start tag with a backslash (/) before the tag name.  Any content will go between the start and end tags.

Some of just a few of the tags used in HTML are:

The text between <html> and </html> describes an HTML document

The text between <head> and </head> provides information about the webpage

The text between <title> and </title> provides a title for the webpage

The text between <body> and </body> describes the visible content on the webpage

The text between <h1> and </h1> describes a heading

The text between <p> and </p> describes a new paragraph

Let's see this in action by creating a new HTML file called basics.html and place this in the file:

Remember to select HTML as the filetype

<html>

<head>

<title>My Webpage</title>

</head>

<body>

<h1>My First Heading</h1>

<p>My first paragraph.<br></p>

<p>My second paragraph.</p>

</body>

</html>

Open this file in your browser to see the result.

Also notice that tags can be nested inside other tags.  For example, our **<title>** tag is nested inside of our **<head>** tag.  And our **<head>** tag is nested inside of the **<html>** tag.  Nested tags are an important concept in markup languages such as HTML.

Also notice that every tag has a start and end tag except for the **<br>** tag.  This tag represents a line break on the page, and doesn't have a start or end tag.  Tags such as < **br>** are called Empty Tags, and do not contain content.  HTML has several other empty tags that represent many other actions on the page.

Challenge Yourself:

Create a webpage with with a small bio about yourself.  The headline of this page should be "About Me", and should include a few paragraphs about where you were born, what school you attend, and something interesting about yourself.  The title of your page should be "<Your Name> Bio", and save the file as an HTML filetype using whatever name you choose.

Images and Attributes

HTML Tags describe the type of content that will be displayed on the webpage.  Many times, these tags need some additional information in order to display content exactly how we would like to see it.  In HTML and other markup languages, we add **Attributes** inside of our tags to provide this additional information.

 <h1 style="color:blue">My First Heading</h1>

In this example above, we added an attribute to our <h1> tag called "style", and set its value to "color:blue".   This will tell your browser to display the content inside the <h1> tag with the color blue.  Try modifying your previous file to the following and open in a browser:

<html>

<head>

<title>My Webpage</title>

</head>

<body style="background-color:lightgrey">

<h1 style="color:blue">My First Heading</h1>

<p style="color:green">My first paragraph.<br></p>

<p style="font-family:courier">My second paragraph.</p>

</body>

</html>

After refreshing your browser, you should see the changes to your content that you specified in your attributes.  In this example above, we added an attribute to our <h1> tag called "style", and set its value to "color:blue".   This will tell your browser to display the content inside the <h1> tag with the color blue.  Try modifying your previous file to the following and open in a browser:
